\section*{Methods}

\subsection*{Species selection and growing conditions}
We used seven species of tree saplings for our experiment (Fuelinex). We arranged the trees in three blocks, each containing all 6 treatments and 7 species, with two of these blocks placed under an open-walled and well-ventilated polytunnel greenhouse. All saplings were connected to a drip irrigation system (40 PVC frame from Netafilm 54 with a Toro controller) to maintain constant irrigation across the season.

\subsection*{Tree measurements and biomass}: 
Using red paint, we marked the trees on their trunk at ~3 cm from the soil in February 2024. Then we measured the diameter at the top of that mark using a digital calliper (accuracy $\pm$ 0.01cm) and height from that mark to the bottom of the highest apical bud with a metal ruler (accuracy $\pm$ 0.1cm). We measured those two same points in the winter (2024 growing season) and in the fall (2025 growing season) of 2025. In the fall of 2025, we destructively collected above ground biomass after measuring diameter and height.

\subsection*{Experimental design} 
Individuals from each species were randomly selected for a full factorial design of Warm/Cool, Spring/Fall treatments with two additional treatments to test nutrient effects in the fall (Figure \ref{fig:Fuelinex_Design2024.pdf}), for a total of 15 replicates/treatment/species. On 6 March 2024, we placed the Cool Spring individuals in climate chambers to delay the start of their growing season, while the Warm Spring replicates remained at ambient conditions. Once all Warm Spring individuals had fully leafed out, we removed the Cool Spring replicates from the chambers and placed them back at ambient conditions for the whole summer. On 4 September 2024, we placed the trees for the Warm Fall treatments in the climate chambers. The temperature was set to fit the mean 30-year weekly maximum temperature of the previous month (e.g. 1st week of September set to the average of the 1st week of August). The Cool Fall treatment trees remained at ambient conditions. We also set the photoperiod regime to the corresponding sunrise and sunset of the ongoing week and ramped it until it reached full light. In 2025, all the trees were kept at ambient conditions together at Totem field during which we recorded the same phenophases.

\subsection*{Statistical analyses}
Using diameter ($RCD$), height ($H$) and above-ground biomass ($B$) for 2025, we fitted two allometric coefficients ($\beta_1$) and($\beta_2$) using the following equation from [Annighöfer*].

\[
\begin{aligned}
B &\sim \text{logNormal}(\mu, \sigma_{allo}) \\
\mu &= \beta_{1} \times \left( RCD^{2} \times H \right)^{\beta_{2}} \\
\beta_{1} &\sim \text{logNormal}(\log(0.5), 0.3) \\
\beta_{2} &\sim \text{Normal}(0.7, 0.2) \\
\sigma_{allo} &\sim \text{Normal}(0, 2)
\end{aligned}
\]

We used the marginal posterior distribution with the error for the two allometric coefficients to estimate the corresponding biomass of the first (2023), second (2024) and the third (2025) diameter and height measurements. Then using a mean biomass point estimate for each tree at each year, we calculated the growing season increment of 2024 ($\Delta B_1$) and 2025 ($\Delta B_2$). Where ($\Delta B_1 = AGB2024 - AGB2023$) and ($\Delta B_2 = AGB2025 - AGB2024$).% [?Should add a hat or something since it's the ypred were using]. 

\subsection*{Carry-over effect model}
Using the estimated biomass increment for 2024 and 2025, we jointly fit $\Delta B_1$ and $\Delta B_2$ using Stan with the rstan package version 2.32.7 \citep{carpenter_stan_2017} to run the Stan code in R. [add priors, chains, rhat, etc.]

% Model structure
\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta B_1 &\sim logNormal(\mu, \sigma_y) \\
\mu &= N (\alpha_{cc1}+ \alpha_{wc1}S_1 + \alpha_{cw1} F_1 + \alpha_{ww1} SF_1) \\
\alpha_{cc1} &\sim logNormal(1,1)\\
\alpha_{wc1} &\sim logNormal(1,1)\\
\alpha_{cw1} &\sim logNormal(1,1)\\
\alpha_{ww1} &\sim logNormal(1,1)\\
\\
\Delta B_2 &\sim logNormal(\mu, \sigma_y) \\
\mu &= N (\alpha_{cc2}+ \alpha_{wc2}S_2 + \alpha_{cw2} F_2 + \alpha_{ww2} SF_2) \\
\alpha_{cc2} &\sim logNormal(1,1)\\
\alpha_{wc2} &\sim logNormal(1,1)\\
\alpha_{cw2} &\sim logNormal(1,1)\\
\alpha_{ww2} &\sim logNormal(1,1)\\
\end{aligned}
\]

\textbf{Where:}
\begin{itemize} 
	\item $\alpha_1$ = Year 1, treatment Cool Spring, Cool Fall (reference value)
	\item $\alpha_1 + \alpha_{S1} = $ Year 1, treatment Warm Spring, Cool Fall
	\item $\alpha_1 + \alpha_{F1} = $ Year 1, treatment Cool Spring, Warm Fall
	\item $\alpha_1 + \alpha_{S1} + \alpha_{F1} + \alpha_{SF1} = $ Year 1, treatment Warm Spring, Warm Fall
	\item $ S1 = $ dummy variable, if it's 1, then Warm spring, else Cool Spring
	\item $ F1 = $ dummy variable, if it's 1, then Warm fall, else Cool fall
	\item $ SF1 = $ dummy variable, for a subadditive effect of a Warm Spring and a Warm Fall treatment.
\end{itemize} 

